172/* The following tries to get a good version of alloca. The tests are
173 adapted from autoconf AC_FUNC_ALLOCA, with a couple of additions.
174 Whether this succeeds is tested by GMP_FUNC_ALLOCA and HAVE_ALLOCA will
175 be setup appropriately.
176
177 ifndef alloca - a cpp define might already exist.
178 glibc <stdlib.h> includes <alloca.h> which uses GCC __builtin_alloca.
179 HP cc +Olibcalls adds a #define of alloca to __builtin_alloca.
180
181 GCC __builtin_alloca - preferred whenever available.
182
183 _AIX pragma - IBM compilers need a #pragma in "each module that needs to
184 use alloca". Pragma indented to protect pre-ANSI cpp's. _IBMR2 was
185 used in past versions of GMP, retained still in case it matters.
186
187 The autoconf manual says this pragma needs to be at the start of a C
188 file, apart from comments and preprocessor directives. Is that true?
189 xlc on aix 4.xxx doesn't seem to mind it being after prototypes etc
190 from gmp.h.
191*/
192
193#ifndef alloca
194# ifdef __GNUC__
195# define alloca __builtin_alloca
196# else
197# ifdef __DECC
198# define alloca(x) __ALLOCA(x)
199# else
200# ifdef _MSC_VER
201# include <malloc.h>
202# define alloca _alloca
203# else
204# if HAVE_ALLOCA_H
205# include <alloca.h>
206# else
207# if defined (_AIX) || defined (_IBMR2)
208 #pragma alloca
209# else
210# if !defined (__NetBSD__)
211 char *alloca ();
212# endif
213# endif
214# endif
215# endif
216# endif
217# endif
218#endif

328/* Usage: TMP_DECL;
329 TMP_MARK;
330 ptr = TMP_ALLOC (bytes);
331 TMP_FREE;
332
333 Small allocations should use TMP_SALLOC, big allocations should use
334 TMP_BALLOC. Allocations that might be small or big should use TMP_ALLOC.
335
336 Functions that use just TMP_SALLOC should use TMP_SDECL, TMP_SMARK, and
337 TMP_SFREE.
338
339 TMP_DECL just declares a variable, but might be empty and so must be last
340 in a list of variables. TMP_MARK must be done before any TMP_ALLOC.
341 TMP_ALLOC(0) is not allowed. TMP_FREE doesn't need to be done if a
342 TMP_MARK was made, but then no TMP_ALLOCs. */
343
344/* The alignment in bytes, used for TMP_ALLOCed blocks, when alloca or
345 __gmp_allocate_func doesn't already determine it. Currently TMP_ALLOC
346 isn't used for "double"s, so that's not in the union. */
347union tmp_align_t {
348 mp_limb_t l;
349 char *p;
350};
351#define __TMP_ALIGN sizeof (union tmp_align_t)

353/* Return "a" rounded upwards to a multiple of "m", if it isn't already.
354 "a" must be an unsigned type.
355 This is designed for use with a compile-time constant "m".
356 The POW2 case is expected to be usual, and gcc 3.0 and up recognises
357 "(-(8*n))%8" or the like is always zero, which means the rounding up in
358 the WANT_TMP_NOTREENTRANT version of TMP_ALLOC below will be a noop. */
359#define ROUND_UP_MULTIPLE(a,m) \
360 (POW2_P(m) ? (a) + (-(a))%(m) \
361 : (a)+(m)-1 - (((a)+(m)-1) % (m)))
362

495/* It's more efficient to allocate one block than many. This is certainly
496 true of the malloc methods, but it can even be true of alloca if that
497 involves copying a chunk of stack (various RISCs), or a call to a stack
498 bounds check (mingw). In any case, when debugging keep separate blocks
499 so a redzoning malloc debugger can protect each individually. */
500#define TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS_2(xp,xsize, yp,ysize) \
501 do { \
502 if (WANT_TMP_DEBUG) \
503 { \
504 (xp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS (xsize); \
505 (yp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS (ysize); \
506 } \
507 else \
508 { \
509 (xp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS ((xsize) + (ysize)); \
510 (yp) = (xp) + (xsize); \
511 } \
512 } while (0)
513#define TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS_3(xp,xsize, yp,ysize, zp,zsize) \
514 do { \
515 if (WANT_TMP_DEBUG) \
516 { \
517 (xp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS (xsize); \
518 (yp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS (ysize); \
519 (zp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS (zsize); \
520 } \
521 else \
522 { \
523 (xp) = TMP_ALLOC_LIMBS ((xsize) + (ysize) + (zsize)); \
524 (yp) = (xp) + (xsize); \
525 (zp) = (yp) + (ysize); \
526 } \
527 } while (0)

739/* In gcc 2.96 and up on i386, tail calls are optimized to jumps if the
740 stack usage is compatible. __attribute__ ((regparm (N))) helps by
741 putting leading parameters in registers, avoiding extra stack.
742
743 regparm cannot be used with calls going through the PLT, because the
744 binding code there may clobber the registers (%eax, %edx, %ecx) used for
745 the regparm parameters. Calls to local (ie. static) functions could
746 still use this, if we cared to differentiate locals and globals.
747
748 On athlon-unknown-freebsd4.9 with gcc 3.3.3, regparm cannot be used with
749 -p or -pg profiling, since that version of gcc doesn't realize the
750 .mcount calls will clobber the parameter registers. Other systems are
751 ok, like debian with glibc 2.3.2 (mcount doesn't clobber), but we don't
752 bother to try to detect this. regparm is only an optimization so we just
753 disable it when profiling (profiling being a slowdown anyway). */
754
755#if HAVE_HOST_CPU_FAMILY_x86 && __GMP_GNUC_PREREQ (2,96) && ! defined (PIC) \
756 && ! WANT_PROFILING_PROF && ! WANT_PROFILING_GPROF
757#define USE_LEADING_REGPARM 1
758#else
759#define USE_LEADING_REGPARM 0
760#endif
761
762/* Macros for altering parameter order according to regparm usage. */
763#if USE_LEADING_REGPARM
764#define REGPARM_2_1(a,b,x) x,a,b
765#define REGPARM_3_1(a,b,c,x) x,a,b,c
766#define REGPARM_ATTR(n) __attribute__ ((regparm (n)))
767#else
768#define REGPARM_2_1(a,b,x) a,b,x
769#define REGPARM_3_1(a,b,c,x) a,b,c,x
770#define REGPARM_ATTR(n)
771#endif

774/* ASM_L gives a local label for a gcc asm block, for use when temporary
775 local labels like "1:" might not be available, which is the case for
776 instance on the x86s (the SCO assembler doesn't support them).
777
778 The label generated is made unique by including "%=" which is a unique
779 number for each insn. This ensures the same name can be used in multiple
780 asm blocks, perhaps via a macro. Since jumps between asm blocks are not
781 allowed there's no need for a label to be usable outside a single
782 block. */
783
784#define ASM_L(name) LSYM_PREFIX "asm_%=_" #name

1259/* For a threshold between algorithms A and B, size>=thresh is where B
1260 should be used. Special value MP_SIZE_T_MAX means only ever use A, or
1261 value 0 means only ever use B. The tests for these special values will
1262 be compile-time constants, so the compiler should be able to eliminate
1263 the code for the unwanted algorithm. */
1264
1265#if ! defined (__GNUC__) || __GNUC__ < 2
1266#define ABOVE_THRESHOLD(size,thresh) \
1267 ((thresh) == 0 \
1268 || ((thresh) != MP_SIZE_T_MAX \
1269 && (size) >= (thresh)))
1270#else
1271#define ABOVE_THRESHOLD(size,thresh) \
1272 ((__builtin_constant_p (thresh) && (thresh) == 0) \
1273 || (!(__builtin_constant_p (thresh) && (thresh) == MP_SIZE_T_MAX) \
1274 && (size) >= (thresh)))
1275#endif
1276#define BELOW_THRESHOLD(size,thresh) (! ABOVE_THRESHOLD (size, thresh))

1834 ppc630 for instance this is optimal since it can sustain only 1 store per
1835 cycle.

1838 "for" loop in the generic code below can become stu/bdnz. The do/while
1839 here helps it get to that. The same caveat about plain -mpowerpc64 mode
1840 applies here as to __GMPN_COPY_INCR in gmp.h.
1841
1842 xlc 3.1 already generates stu/bdnz from the generic C, and does so from
1843 this loop too.

1846 at a time. MPN_ZERO isn't all that important in GMP, so it might be more

1848 would be good when on a GNU system. */

1917/* Strip least significant zero limbs from {ptr,size} by incrementing ptr
1918 and decrementing size. low should be ptr[0], and will be the new ptr[0]
1919 on returning. The number in {ptr,size} must be non-zero, ie. size!=0 and
1920 somewhere a non-zero limb. */
1921#define MPN_STRIP_LOW_ZEROS_NOT_ZERO(ptr, size, low) \
1922 do { \
1923 ASSERT ((size) >= 1); \
1924 ASSERT ((low) == (ptr)[0]); \
1925 \
1926 while ((low) == 0) \
1927 { \
1928 (size)--; \
1929 ASSERT ((size) >= 1); \
1930 (ptr)++; \
1931 (low) = *(ptr); \
1932 } \
1933 } while (0)

1970/* MPN_FIB2_SIZE(n) is the size in limbs required by mpn_fib2_ui for fp and
1971 f1p.
1972
1973 From Knuth vol 1 section 1.2.8, F[n] = phi^n/sqrt(5) rounded to the
1974 nearest integer, where phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. So the
1975 number of bits required is n*log_2((1+sqrt(5))/2) = n*0.6942419.
1976
1977 The multiplier used is 23/32=0.71875 for efficient calculation on CPUs
1978 without good floating point. There's +2 for rounding up, and a further
1979 +2 since at the last step x limbs are doubled into a 2x+1 limb region
1980 whereas the actual F[2k] value might be only 2x-1 limbs.
1981
1982 Note that a division is done first, since on a 32-bit system it's at
1983 least conceivable to go right up to n==ULONG_MAX. (F[2^32-1] would be
1984 about 380Mbytes, plus temporary workspace of about 1.2Gbytes here and
1985 whatever a multiply of two 190Mbyte numbers takes.)
1986
1987 Enhancement: When GMP_NUMB_BITS is not a power of 2 the division could be
1988 worked into the multiplier. */
1989
1990#define MPN_FIB2_SIZE(n) \
1991 ((mp_size_t) ((n) / 32 * 23 / GMP_NUMB_BITS) + 4)

2339/* Return non-zero if xp,xsize and yp,ysize overlap.
2340 If xp+xsize<=yp there's no overlap, or if yp+ysize<=xp there's no
2341 overlap. If both these are false, there's an overlap. */
2342#define MPN_OVERLAP_P(xp, xsize, yp, ysize) \
2343 ((xp) + (xsize) > (yp) && (yp) + (ysize) > (xp))
2344#define MEM_OVERLAP_P(xp, xsize, yp, ysize) \
2345 ( (char *) (xp) + (xsize) > (char *) (yp) \
2346 && (char *) (yp) + (ysize) > (char *) (xp))
2347
2348/* Return non-zero if xp,xsize and yp,ysize are either identical or not
2349 overlapping. Return zero if they're partially overlapping. */
2350#define MPN_SAME_OR_SEPARATE_P(xp, yp, size) \
2351 MPN_SAME_OR_SEPARATE2_P(xp, size, yp, size)
2352#define MPN_SAME_OR_SEPARATE2_P(xp, xsize, yp, ysize) \
2353 ((xp) == (yp) || ! MPN_OVERLAP_P (xp, xsize, yp, ysize))
2354
2355/* Return non-zero if dst,dsize and src,ssize are either identical or
2356 overlapping in a way suitable for an incrementing/decrementing algorithm.
2357 Return zero if they're partially overlapping in an unsuitable fashion. */
2358#define MPN_SAME_OR_INCR2_P(dst, dsize, src, ssize) \
2359 ((dst) <= (src) || ! MPN_OVERLAP_P (dst, dsize, src, ssize))
2360#define MPN_SAME_OR_INCR_P(dst, src, size) \
2361 MPN_SAME_OR_INCR2_P(dst, size, src, size)
2362#define MPN_SAME_OR_DECR2_P(dst, dsize, src, ssize) \
2363 ((dst) >= (src) || ! MPN_OVERLAP_P (dst, dsize, src, ssize))
2364#define MPN_SAME_OR_DECR_P(dst, src, size) \
2365 MPN_SAME_OR_DECR2_P(dst, size, src, size)

2368/* ASSERT() is a private assertion checking scheme, similar to <assert.h>.

2642/* MPN_INCR_U does {ptr,size} += n, MPN_DECR_U does {ptr,size} -= n, both
2643 expecting no carry (or borrow) from that.
2644
2645 The size parameter is only for the benefit of assertion checking. In a
2646 normal build it's unused and the carry/borrow is just propagated as far
2647 as it needs to go.
2648
2649 On random data, usually only one or two limbs of {ptr,size} get updated,
2650 so there's no need for any sophisticated looping, just something compact
2651 and sensible.
2652
2653 FIXME: Switch all code from mpn_{incr,decr}_u to MPN_{INCR,DECR}_U,
2654 declaring their operand sizes, then remove the former. This is purely
2655 for the benefit of assertion checking. */
2656
2657#if defined (__GNUC__) && GMP_NAIL_BITS == 0 && ! defined (NO_ASM) \
2658 && (defined(HAVE_HOST_CPU_FAMILY_x86) || defined(HAVE_HOST_CPU_FAMILY_x86_64)) \
2659 && ! WANT_ASSERT
2660/* Better flags handling than the generic C gives on i386, saving a few
2661 bytes of code and maybe a cycle or two. */
2662
2663#define MPN_IORD_U(ptr, incr, aors) \
2664 do { \
2665 mp_ptr __ptr_dummy; \
2666 if (__builtin_constant_p (incr) && (incr) == 0) \
2667 { \
2668 } \
2669 else if (__builtin_constant_p (incr) && (incr) == 1) \
2670 { \
2671 __asm__ __volatile__ \
2672 ("\n" ASM_L(top) ":\n" \
2673 "\t" aors "\t$1, (%0)\n" \
2674 "\tlea\t%c2(%0), %0\n" \
2675 "\tjc\t" ASM_L(top) \
2676 : "=r" (__ptr_dummy) \
2677 : "0" (ptr), "n" (sizeof(mp_limb_t)) \
2678 : "memory"); \
2679 } \
2680 else \
2681 { \
2682 __asm__ __volatile__ \
2683 ( aors "\t%2, (%0)\n" \
2684 "\tjnc\t" ASM_L(done) "\n" \
2685 ASM_L(top) ":\n" \
2686 "\t" aors "\t$1, %c3(%0)\n" \
2687 "\tlea\t%c3(%0), %0\n" \
2688 "\tjc\t" ASM_L(top) "\n" \
2689 ASM_L(done) ":\n" \
2690 : "=r" (__ptr_dummy) \
2691 : "0" (ptr), \
2692 "re" ((mp_limb_t) (incr)), "n" (sizeof(mp_limb_t)) \
2693 : "memory"); \
2694 } \
2695 } while (0)

2697#if GMP_LIMB_BITS == 32

2840/* Structure for conversion between internal binary format and strings. */
2841struct bases
2842{
2843 /* Number of digits in the conversion base that always fits in an mp_limb_t.
2844 For example, for base 10 on a machine where an mp_limb_t has 32 bits this
2845 is 9, since 10**9 is the largest number that fits into an mp_limb_t. */
2846 int chars_per_limb;
2847
2848 /* log(2)/log(conversion_base) */
2849 mp_limb_t logb2;
2850
2851 /* log(conversion_base)/log(2) */
2852 mp_limb_t log2b;
2853
2854 /* base**chars_per_limb, i.e. the biggest number that fits a word, built by
2855 factors of base. Exception: For 2, 4, 8, etc, big_base is log2(base),
2856 i.e. the number of bits used to represent each digit in the base. */
2857 mp_limb_t big_base;
2858
2859 /* A GMP_LIMB_BITS bit approximation to 1/big_base, represented as a
2860 fixed-point number. Instead of dividing by big_base an application can
2861 choose to multiply by big_base_inverted. */
2862 mp_limb_t big_base_inverted;
2863};
2864
2865#define mp_bases __MPN(bases)
2866__GMP_DECLSPEC extern const struct bases mp_bases[257];

2869/* Compute the number of digits in base for nbits bits, making sure the result
2870 is never too small. The two variants of the macro implement the same
2871 function; the GT2 variant below works just for bases > 2. */
2872#define DIGITS_IN_BASE_FROM_BITS(res, nbits, b) \
2873 do { \
2874 mp_limb_t _ph, _dummy; \
2875 size_t _nbits = (nbits); \
2876 umul_ppmm (_ph, _dummy, mp_bases[b].logb2, _nbits); \
2877 _ph += (_dummy + _nbits < _dummy); \
2878 res = _ph + 1; \
2879 } while (0)
2880#define DIGITS_IN_BASEGT2_FROM_BITS(res, nbits, b) \
2881 do { \
2882 mp_limb_t _ph, _dummy; \
2883 size_t _nbits = (nbits); \
2884 umul_ppmm (_ph, _dummy, mp_bases[b].logb2 + 1, _nbits); \
2885 res = _ph + 1; \
2886 } while (0)
2887
2888/* For power of 2 bases this is exact. For other bases the result is either
2889 exact or one too big.
2890
2891 To be exact always it'd be necessary to examine all the limbs of the
2892 operand, since numbers like 100..000 and 99...999 generally differ only
2893 in the lowest limb. It'd be possible to examine just a couple of high
2894 limbs to increase the probability of being exact, but that doesn't seem
2895 worth bothering with. */
2896
2897#define MPN_SIZEINBASE(result, ptr, size, base) \
2898 do { \
2899 int __lb_base, __cnt; \
2900 size_t __totbits; \
2901 \
2902 ASSERT ((size) >= 0); \
2903 ASSERT ((base) >= 2); \
2904 ASSERT ((base) < numberof (mp_bases)); \
2905 \
2906 /* Special case for X == 0. */ \
2907 if ((size) == 0) \
2908 (result) = 1; \
2909 else \
2910 { \
2911 /* Calculate the total number of significant bits of X. */ \
2912 count_leading_zeros (__cnt, (ptr)[(size)-1]); \
2913 __totbits = (size_t) (size) * GMP_NUMB_BITS - (__cnt - GMP_NAIL_BITS);\
2914 \
2915 if (POW2_P (base)) \
2916 { \
2917 __lb_base = mp_bases[base].big_base; \
2918 (result) = (__totbits + __lb_base - 1) / __lb_base; \
2919 } \
2920 else \
2921 { \
2922 DIGITS_IN_BASEGT2_FROM_BITS (result, __totbits, base); \
2923 } \
2924 } \
2925 } while (0)
2926
2927#define MPN_SIZEINBASE_2EXP(result, ptr, size, base2exp) \
2928 do { \
2929 int __cnt; \
2930 mp_bitcnt_t __totbits; \
2931 ASSERT ((size) > 0); \
2932 ASSERT ((ptr)[(size)-1] != 0); \
2933 count_leading_zeros (__cnt, (ptr)[(size)-1]); \
2934 __totbits = (mp_bitcnt_t) (size) * GMP_NUMB_BITS - (__cnt - GMP_NAIL_BITS); \
2935 (result) = (__totbits + (base2exp)-1) / (base2exp); \
2936 } while (0)

2982 or 0 there into a limb 0xFF..FF or 0 respectively.
2983
2984 On most CPUs this is just an arithmetic right shift by GMP_LIMB_BITS-1,
2985 but C99 doesn't guarantee signed right shifts are arithmetic, so we have

2987 necessary for instance on Cray vector systems.
2988
2989 Recent versions of gcc (eg. 3.3) will in fact optimize a "? :" like this
2990 to an arithmetic right shift anyway, but it's good to get the desired

2997 : (n) & GMP_LIMB_HIGHBIT ? MP_LIMB_T_MAX : CNST_LIMB(0))

3048/* udiv_qrnnd_preinv -- Based on work by Niels Mller and Torbjrn Granlund.
3049 We write things strangely below, to help gcc. A more straightforward
3050 version:
3051 _r = (nl) - _qh * (d);
3052 _t = _r + (d);
3053 if (_r >= _ql)
3054 {
3055 _qh--;
3056 _r = _t;
3057 }
3058 For one operation shorter critical path, one may want to use this form:
3059 _p = _qh * (d)
3060 _s = (nl) + (d);
3061 _r = (nl) - _p;
3062 _t = _s - _p;
3063 if (_r >= _ql)
3064 {
3065 _qh--;
3066 _r = _t;
3067 }
3068*/
3069#define udiv_qrnnd_preinv(q, r, nh, nl, d, di) \
3070 do { \
3071 mp_limb_t _qh, _ql, _r, _mask; \
3072 umul_ppmm (_qh, _ql, (nh), (di)); \
3073 if (__builtin_constant_p (nl) && (nl) == 0) \
3074 { \
3075 _qh += (nh) + 1; \
3076 _r = - _qh * (d); \
3077 _mask = -(mp_limb_t) (_r > _ql); /* both > and >= are OK */ \
3078 _qh += _mask; \
3079 _r += _mask & (d); \
3080 } \
3081 else \
3082 { \
3083 add_ssaaaa (_qh, _ql, _qh, _ql, (nh) + 1, (nl)); \
3084 _r = (nl) - _qh * (d); \
3085 _mask = -(mp_limb_t) (_r > _ql); /* both > and >= are OK */ \
3086 _qh += _mask; \
3087 _r += _mask & (d); \
3088 if (UNLIKELY (_r >= (d))) \
3089 { \
3090 _r -= (d); \
3091 _qh++; \
3092 } \
3093 } \
3094 (r) = _r; \
3095 (q) = _qh; \
3096 } while (0)

3123/* Compute quotient the quotient and remainder for n / d. Requires d
3124 >= B^2 / 2 and n < d B. di is the inverse

3126 floor ((B^3 - 1) / (d0 + d1 B)) - B.

3129 and outputs may overlap.

3238/* binvert_limb() sets inv to the multiplicative inverse of n modulo
3239 2^GMP_NUMB_BITS, ie. satisfying inv*n == 1 mod 2^GMP_NUMB_BITS.
3240 n must be odd (otherwise such an inverse doesn't exist).

3242 This is not to be confused with invert_limb(), which is completely
3243 different.

3245 The table lookup gives an inverse with the low 8 bits valid, and each
3246 multiply step doubles the number of bits. See Jebelean "An algorithm for
3247 exact division" end of section 4 (reference in gmp.texi).
3248

3851/* On m68k, x86 and amd64, gcc (and maybe other compilers) can hold doubles
3852 in the coprocessor, which means a bigger exponent range than normal, and
3853 depending on the rounding mode, a bigger mantissa than normal. (See
3854 "Disappointments" in the gcc manual.) FORCE_DOUBLE stores and fetches
3855 "d" through memory to force any rounding and overflows to occur.
3856
3857 On amd64, and on x86s with SSE2, gcc (depending on options) uses the xmm
3858 registers, where there's no such extra precision and no need for the
3859 FORCE_DOUBLE. We don't bother to detect this since the present uses for
3860 FORCE_DOUBLE are only in test programs and default generic C code.
3861
3862 Not quite sure that an "automatic volatile" will use memory, but it does
3863 in gcc. An asm("":"=m"(d):"0"(d)) can't be used to trick gcc, since
3864 apparently matching operands like "0" are only allowed on a register
3865 output. gcc 3.4 warns about this, though in fact it and past versions
3866 seem to put the operand through memory as hoped. */

3869 || defined (__amd64__))

3871 do { volatile double __gmp_force = (d); (d) = __gmp_force; } while (0)
3872#else
3873#define FORCE_DOUBLE(d) do { } while (0)

3926/* BIT1 means a result value in bit 1 (second least significant bit), with a
3927 zero bit representing +1 and a one bit representing -1. Bits other than
3928 bit 1 are garbage. These are meant to be kept in "int"s, and casts are
3929 used to ensure the expressions are "int"s even if a and/or b might be
3930 other types.
3931
3932 JACOBI_TWOS_U_BIT1 and JACOBI_RECIP_UU_BIT1 are used in mpn_jacobi_base
3933 and their speed is important. Expressions are used rather than
3934 conditionals to accumulate sign changes, which effectively means XORs
3935 instead of conditional JUMPs. */
3936
3937/* (a/0), with a signed; is 1 if a=+/-1, 0 otherwise */
3938#define JACOBI_S0(a) (((a) == 1) | ((a) == -1))
3939
3940/* (a/0), with a unsigned; is 1 if a=+/-1, 0 otherwise */
3941#define JACOBI_U0(a) ((a) == 1)
3942
3943/* FIXME: JACOBI_LS0 and JACOBI_0LS are the same, so delete one and
3944 come up with a better name. */
3945
3946/* (a/0), with a given by low and size;
3947 is 1 if a=+/-1, 0 otherwise */
3948#define JACOBI_LS0(alow,asize) \
3949 (((asize) == 1 || (asize) == -1) && (alow) == 1)
3950
3951/* (a/0), with a an mpz_t;
3952 fetch of low limb always valid, even if size is zero */
3953#define JACOBI_Z0(a) JACOBI_LS0 (PTR(a)[0], SIZ(a))
3954
3955/* (0/b), with b unsigned; is 1 if b=1, 0 otherwise */
3956#define JACOBI_0U(b) ((b) == 1)
3957
3958/* (0/b), with b unsigned; is 1 if b=+/-1, 0 otherwise */
3959#define JACOBI_0S(b) ((b) == 1 || (b) == -1)
3960
3961/* (0/b), with b given by low and size; is 1 if b=+/-1, 0 otherwise */
3962#define JACOBI_0LS(blow,bsize) \
3963 (((bsize) == 1 || (bsize) == -1) && (blow) == 1)
3964
3965/* Convert a bit1 to +1 or -1. */
3966#define JACOBI_BIT1_TO_PN(result_bit1) \
3967 (1 - ((int) (result_bit1) & 2))
3968
3969/* (2/b), with b unsigned and odd;
3970 is (-1)^((b^2-1)/8) which is 1 if b==1,7mod8 or -1 if b==3,5mod8 and
3971 hence obtained from (b>>1)^b */
3972#define JACOBI_TWO_U_BIT1(b) \
3973 ((int) (((b) >> 1) ^ (b)))
3974
3975/* (2/b)^twos, with b unsigned and odd */
3976#define JACOBI_TWOS_U_BIT1(twos, b) \
3977 ((int) ((twos) << 1) & JACOBI_TWO_U_BIT1 (b))
3978
3979/* (2/b)^twos, with b unsigned and odd */
3980#define JACOBI_TWOS_U(twos, b) \
3981 (JACOBI_BIT1_TO_PN (JACOBI_TWOS_U_BIT1 (twos, b)))
3982
3983/* (-1/b), with b odd (signed or unsigned);
3984 is (-1)^((b-1)/2) */
3985#define JACOBI_N1B_BIT1(b) \
3986 ((int) (b))
3987
3988/* (a/b) effect due to sign of a: signed/unsigned, b odd;
3989 is (-1/b) if a<0, or +1 if a>=0 */
3990#define JACOBI_ASGN_SU_BIT1(a, b) \
3991 ((((a) < 0) << 1) & JACOBI_N1B_BIT1(b))
3992
3993/* (a/b) effect due to sign of b: signed/signed;
3994 is -1 if a and b both negative, +1 otherwise */
3995#define JACOBI_BSGN_SS_BIT1(a, b) \
3996 ((((a)<0) & ((b)<0)) << 1)
3997
3998/* (a/b) effect due to sign of b: signed/mpz;
3999 is -1 if a and b both negative, +1 otherwise */
4000#define JACOBI_BSGN_SZ_BIT1(a, b) \
4001 JACOBI_BSGN_SS_BIT1 (a, SIZ(b))
4002
4003/* (a/b) effect due to sign of b: mpz/signed;
4004 is -1 if a and b both negative, +1 otherwise */
4005#define JACOBI_BSGN_ZS_BIT1(a, b) \
4006 JACOBI_BSGN_SZ_BIT1 (b, a)
4007
4008/* (a/b) reciprocity to switch to (b/a), a,b both unsigned and odd;
4009 is (-1)^((a-1)*(b-1)/4), which means +1 if either a,b==1mod4, or -1 if
4010 both a,b==3mod4, achieved in bit 1 by a&b. No ASSERT()s about a,b odd
4011 because this is used in a couple of places with only bit 1 of a or b
4012 valid. */
4013#define JACOBI_RECIP_UU_BIT1(a, b) \
4014 ((int) ((a) & (b)))
4015
4016/* Strip low zero limbs from {b_ptr,b_size} by incrementing b_ptr and
4017 decrementing b_size. b_low should be b_ptr[0] on entry, and will be
4018 updated for the new b_ptr. result_bit1 is updated according to the
4019 factors of 2 stripped, as per (a/2). */
4020#define JACOBI_STRIP_LOW_ZEROS(result_bit1, a, b_ptr, b_size, b_low) \
4021 do { \
4022 ASSERT ((b_size) >= 1); \
4023 ASSERT ((b_low) == (b_ptr)[0]); \
4024 \
4025 while (UNLIKELY ((b_low) == 0)) \
4026 { \
4027 (b_size)--; \
4028 ASSERT ((b_size) >= 1); \
4029 (b_ptr)++; \
4030 (b_low) = *(b_ptr); \
4031 \
4032 ASSERT (((a) & 1) != 0); \
4033 if ((GMP_NUMB_BITS % 2) == 1) \
4034 (result_bit1) ^= JACOBI_TWO_U_BIT1(a); \
4035 } \
4036 } while (0)
4037
4038/* Set a_rem to {a_ptr,a_size} reduced modulo b, either using mod_1 or
4039 modexact_1_odd, but in either case leaving a_rem<b. b must be odd and
4040 unsigned. modexact_1_odd effectively calculates -a mod b, and
4041 result_bit1 is adjusted for the factor of -1.
4042
4043 The way mpn_modexact_1_odd sometimes bases its remainder on a_size and
4044 sometimes on a_size-1 means if GMP_NUMB_BITS is odd we can't know what
4045 factor to introduce into result_bit1, so for that case use mpn_mod_1
4046 unconditionally.
4047
4048 FIXME: mpn_modexact_1_odd is more efficient, so some way to get it used
4049 for odd GMP_NUMB_BITS would be good. Perhaps it could mung its result,
4050 or not skip a divide step, or something. */
4051
4052#define JACOBI_MOD_OR_MODEXACT_1_ODD(result_bit1, a_rem, a_ptr, a_size, b) \
4053 do { \
4054 mp_srcptr __a_ptr = (a_ptr); \
4055 mp_size_t __a_size = (a_size); \
4056 mp_limb_t __b = (b); \
4057 \
4058 ASSERT (__a_size >= 1); \
4059 ASSERT (__b & 1); \
4060 \
4061 if ((GMP_NUMB_BITS % 2) != 0 \
4062 || ABOVE_THRESHOLD (__a_size, BMOD_1_TO_MOD_1_THRESHOLD)) \
4063 { \
4064 (a_rem) = mpn_mod_1 (__a_ptr, __a_size, __b); \
4065 } \
4066 else \
4067 { \
4068 (result_bit1) ^= JACOBI_N1B_BIT1 (__b); \
4069 (a_rem) = mpn_modexact_1_odd (__a_ptr, __a_size, __b); \
4070 } \
4071 } while (0)

4073/* State for the Jacobi computation using Lehmer. */
4074#define jacobi_table __gmp_jacobi_table
4075__GMP_DECLSPEC extern const unsigned char jacobi_table[208];
4076
4077/* Bit layout for the initial state. b must be odd.
4078
4079 3 2 1 0
4080 +--+--+--+--+
4081 |a1|a0|b1| s|
4082 +--+--+--+--+
4083
4084 */
4085static inline unsigned
4086mpn_jacobi_init (unsigned a, unsigned b, unsigned s)
4087{
4088 ASSERT (b & 1);
4089 ASSERT (s <= 1);
4090 return ((a & 3) << 2) + (b & 2) + s;
4091}
4092
4093static inline int
4094mpn_jacobi_finish (unsigned bits)
4095{
4096 /* (a, b) = (1,0) or (0,1) */
4097 ASSERT ( (bits & 14) == 0);
4098
4099 return 1-2*(bits & 1);
4100}

4102static inline unsigned
4103mpn_jacobi_update (unsigned bits, unsigned denominator, unsigned q)
4104{
4105 /* FIXME: Could halve table size by not including the e bit in the
4106 * index, and instead xor when updating. Then the lookup would be
4107 * like
4108 *
4109 * bits ^= table[((bits & 30) << 2) + (denominator << 2) + q];
4110 */
4111
4112 ASSERT (bits < 26);
4113 ASSERT (denominator < 2);
4114 ASSERT (q < 4);
4115
4116 /* For almost all calls, denominator is constant and quite often q
4117 is constant too. So use addition rather than or, so the compiler
4118 can put the constant part can into the offset of an indexed
4119 addressing instruction.
4120
4121 With constant denominator, the below table lookup is compiled to
4122
4123 C Constant q = 1, constant denominator = 1
4124 movzbl table+5(%eax,8), %eax
4125
4126 or
4127
4128 C q in %edx, constant denominator = 1
4129 movzbl table+4(%edx,%eax,8), %eax
4130
4131 One could maintain the state preshifted 3 bits, to save a shift
4132 here, but at least on x86, that's no real saving.
4133 */
4134 return bits = jacobi_table[(bits << 3) + (denominator << 2) + q];
4135}

4315/* __GMPF_BITS_TO_PREC applies a minimum 53 bits, rounds upwards to a whole
4316 limb and adds an extra limb. __GMPF_PREC_TO_BITS drops that extra limb,
4317 hence giving back the user's size in bits rounded up. Notice that
4318 converting prec->bits->prec gives an unchanged value. */
4319#define __GMPF_BITS_TO_PREC(n) \
4320 ((mp_size_t) ((__GMP_MAX (53, n) + 2 * GMP_NUMB_BITS - 1) / GMP_NUMB_BITS))
4321#define __GMPF_PREC_TO_BITS(n) \
4322 ((mp_bitcnt_t) (n) * GMP_NUMB_BITS - GMP_NUMB_BITS)
4323
4324__GMP_DECLSPEC extern mp_size_t __gmp_default_fp_limb_precision;

4326/* Compute the number of base-b digits corresponding to nlimbs limbs, rounding
4327 down. */
4328#define DIGITS_IN_BASE_PER_LIMB(res, nlimbs, b) \
4329 do { \
4330 mp_limb_t _ph, _dummy; \
4331 umul_ppmm (_ph, _dummy, \
4332 mp_bases[b].logb2, GMP_NUMB_BITS * (mp_limb_t) (nlimbs));\
4333 res = _ph; \
4334 } while (0)
4335
4336/* Compute the number of limbs corresponding to ndigits base-b digits, rounding
4337 up. */
4338#define LIMBS_PER_DIGIT_IN_BASE(res, ndigits, b) \
4339 do { \
4340 mp_limb_t _ph, _dummy; \
4341 umul_ppmm (_ph, _dummy, mp_bases[b].log2b, (mp_limb_t) (ndigits)); \
4342 res = 8 * _ph / GMP_NUMB_BITS + 2; \
4343 } while (0)
4344
4345
4346/* Set n to the number of significant digits an mpf of the given _mp_prec
4347 field, in the given base. This is a rounded up value, designed to ensure
4348 there's enough digits to reproduce all the guaranteed part of the value.
4349
4350 There are prec many limbs, but the high might be only "1" so forget it
4351 and just count prec-1 limbs into chars. +1 rounds that upwards, and a
4352 further +1 is because the limbs usually won't fall on digit boundaries.
4353
4354 FIXME: If base is a power of 2 and the bits per digit divides
4355 GMP_LIMB_BITS then the +2 is unnecessary. This happens always for
4356 base==2, and in base==16 with the current 32 or 64 bit limb sizes. */
4357
4358#define MPF_SIGNIFICANT_DIGITS(n, base, prec) \
4359 do { \
4360 size_t rawn; \
4361 ASSERT (base >= 2 && base < numberof (mp_bases)); \
4362 DIGITS_IN_BASE_PER_LIMB (rawn, (prec) - 1, base); \
4363 n = rawn + 2; \
4364 } while (0)

4440/* "buf" is a __gmp_allocate_func block of "alloc" many bytes. The first
4441 "size" of these have been written. "alloc > size" is maintained, so
4442 there's room to store a '\0' at the end. "result" is where the
4443 application wants the final block pointer. */
4444struct gmp_asprintf_t {
4445 char **result;
4446 char *buf;
4447 size_t size;
4448 size_t alloc;
4449};
4450
4451#define GMP_ASPRINTF_T_INIT(d, output) \
4452 do { \
4453 (d).result = (output); \
4454 (d).alloc = 256; \
4455 (d).buf = (char *) (*__gmp_allocate_func) ((d).alloc); \
4456 (d).size = 0; \
4457 } while (0)
4458
4459/* If a realloc is necessary, use twice the size actually required, so as to
4460 avoid repeated small reallocs. */
4461#define GMP_ASPRINTF_T_NEED(d, n) \
4462 do { \
4463 size_t alloc, newsize, newalloc; \
4464 ASSERT ((d)->alloc >= (d)->size + 1); \
4465 \
4466 alloc = (d)->alloc; \
4467 newsize = (d)->size + (n); \
4468 if (alloc <= newsize) \
4469 { \
4470 newalloc = 2*newsize; \
4471 (d)->alloc = newalloc; \
4472 (d)->buf = __GMP_REALLOCATE_FUNC_TYPE ((d)->buf, \
4473 alloc, newalloc, char); \
4474 } \
4475 } while (0)

5051/* toom22/toom2: Scratch need is 2*(an + k), k is the recursion depth.
5052 k is ths smallest k such that
5053 ceil(an/2^k) < MUL_TOOM22_THRESHOLD.
5054 which implies that
5055 k = bitsize of floor ((an-1)/(MUL_TOOM22_THRESHOLD-1))
5056 = 1 + floor (log_2 (floor ((an-1)/(MUL_TOOM22_THRESHOLD-1))))
5057*/
5058#define mpn_toom22_mul_itch(an, bn) \
5059 (2 * ((an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS))
5060#define mpn_toom2_sqr_itch(an) \
5061 (2 * ((an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS))
5062
5063/* toom33/toom3: Scratch need is 5an/2 + 10k, k is the recursion depth.
5064 We use 3an + C, so that we can use a smaller constant.
5065 */
5066#define mpn_toom33_mul_itch(an, bn) \
5067 (3 * (an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS)
5068#define mpn_toom3_sqr_itch(an) \
5069 (3 * (an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS)
5070
5071/* toom33/toom3: Scratch need is 8an/3 + 13k, k is the recursion depth.
5072 We use 3an + C, so that we can use a smaller constant.
5073 */
5074#define mpn_toom44_mul_itch(an, bn) \
5075 (3 * (an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS)
5076#define mpn_toom4_sqr_itch(an) \
5077 (3 * (an) + GMP_NUMB_BITS)
5078
5079#define mpn_toom6_sqr_itch(n) \
5080 (((n) - SQR_TOOM6_THRESHOLD)*2 + \
5081 MAX(SQR_TOOM6_THRESHOLD*2 + GMP_NUMB_BITS*6, \
5082 mpn_toom4_sqr_itch(SQR_TOOM6_THRESHOLD)))
5083
5084#define MUL_TOOM6H_MIN \
5085 ((MUL_TOOM6H_THRESHOLD > MUL_TOOM44_THRESHOLD) ? \
5086 MUL_TOOM6H_THRESHOLD : MUL_TOOM44_THRESHOLD)
5087#define mpn_toom6_mul_n_itch(n) \
5088 (((n) - MUL_TOOM6H_MIN)*2 + \
5089 MAX(MUL_TOOM6H_MIN*2 + GMP_NUMB_BITS*6, \
5090 mpn_toom44_mul_itch(MUL_TOOM6H_MIN,MUL_TOOM6H_MIN)))
5091
5092static inline mp_size_t
5093mpn_toom6h_mul_itch (mp_size_t an, mp_size_t bn) {
5094 mp_size_t estimatedN;
5095 estimatedN = (an + bn) / (size_t) 10 + 1;
5096 return mpn_toom6_mul_n_itch (estimatedN * 6);
5097}
5098
5099#define mpn_toom8_sqr_itch(n) \
5100 ((((n)*15)>>3) - ((SQR_TOOM8_THRESHOLD*15)>>3) + \
5101 MAX(((SQR_TOOM8_THRESHOLD*15)>>3) + GMP_NUMB_BITS*6, \
5102 mpn_toom6_sqr_itch(SQR_TOOM8_THRESHOLD)))
5103
5104#define MUL_TOOM8H_MIN \
5105 ((MUL_TOOM8H_THRESHOLD > MUL_TOOM6H_MIN) ? \
5106 MUL_TOOM8H_THRESHOLD : MUL_TOOM6H_MIN)
5107#define mpn_toom8_mul_n_itch(n) \
5108 ((((n)*15)>>3) - ((MUL_TOOM8H_MIN*15)>>3) + \
5109 MAX(((MUL_TOOM8H_MIN*15)>>3) + GMP_NUMB_BITS*6, \
5110 mpn_toom6_mul_n_itch(MUL_TOOM8H_MIN)))

5113mpn_toom8h_mul_itch (mp_size_t an, mp_size_t bn) {
5114 mp_size_t estimatedN;
5115 estimatedN = (an + bn) / (size_t) 14 + 1;
5116 return mpn_toom8_mul_n_itch (estimatedN * 8);
5117}

5191/* A little helper for a null-terminated __gmp_allocate_func string.
5192 The destructor ensures it's freed even if an exception is thrown.
5193 The len field is needed by the destructor, and can be used by anyone else
5194 to avoid a second strlen pass over the data.
5195
5196 Since our input is a C string, using strlen is correct. Perhaps it'd be
5197 more C++-ish style to use std::char_traits<char>::length, but char_traits
5198 isn't available in gcc 2.95.4. */
5199
5200class gmp_allocated_string {
5201 public:
5202 char *str;
5203 size_t len;
5204 gmp_allocated_string(char *arg)
5205 {
5206 str = arg;
5207 len = std::strlen (str);
5208 }
5209 ~gmp_allocated_string()
5210 {
5211 (*__gmp_free_func) (str, len+1);
5212 }
5213};
